ext","url":"/docs","content":"A TypeScript library for parsing Markdown into typed objects and serializing them back using declarative generator-based formats."},"269":{"id":"/docs-1","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"Why datamark?"},"270":{"id":"/docs-2","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#a-10-second-demo","content":"A 10-second demo"},"271":{"id":"/docs-3","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#what-datamark-is-not","content":"What datamark is NOT"},"272":{"id":"/docs-4","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#who-is-it-for","content":"Who is it for?"},"273":{"id":"/docs-5","page_id":"/docs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Quick navigation"},"274":{"id":"/docs-6","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"datamark is a TypeScript library for turning Markdown documents into typed objects — and back again. It gives you a **declarative, generator-based format system** where you define how a document is consumed using combinators like `heading(1)`, `splitByCombinator(heading(2))`, and `many(codeBlock())`."},"275":{"id":"/docs-7","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"AST SDK\" description=\"Parse documents, extract frontmatter, query the AST\" href=\"/docs/core\" />"},"276":{"id":"/docs-8","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Format SDK\" description=\"Define bidirectional formats with datamark()\" href=\"/docs/template\" />"},"277":{"id":"/docs-9","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Examples\" description=\"Real-world format definitions for common patterns\" href=\"/docs/examples\" />"},"278":{"id":"/docs-10","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs","content":"<Card title=\"Comparisons\" description=\"How datamark compares to alternatives\" href=\"/compare\" />"},"279":{"id":"/docs-11","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"Markdown is the universal format for structured text, but parsing it into typed data usually means one of two things:"},"280":{"id":"/docs-12","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"**Regex and string manipulation** — fragile, unreadable, unmaintainable."},"281":{"id":"/docs-13","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"**Abstract syntax trees** — powerful, but you still write imperative traversal code."},"282":{"id":"/docs-14","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"datamark gives you a third option: **declare the shape of your document and get the shape of your data**."},"283":{"id":"/docs-15","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"A format is a pair of generator functions. The `parse` generator consumes the AST using `yield*` combinators. The `stringify` generator emits nodes back into Markdown. Both share the same mental model."},"284":{"id":"/docs-16","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#why-datamark","content":"**Bring your own validator.** datamark uses the Standard Schema v1 interface, so Zod, Valibot, ArkType, TypeBox, and any compliant library work out of the box."},"285":{"id":"/docs-17","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#what-datamark-is-not","content":"**It is not a static site generator.** It parses and transforms Markdown, but it does not build HTML pages or apply themes."},"286":{"id":"/docs-18","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#what-datamark-is-not","content":"**It is not a Markdown renderer.** It produces data, not HTML."},"287":{"id":"/docs-19","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#what-datamark-is-not","content":"**It does not stream.** Input string in, typed object out."},"288":{"id":"/docs-20","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#what-datamark-is-not","content":"**It is not a general-purpose parser generator.** It is specifically designed for Markdown documents."},"289":{"id":"/docs-21","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#who-is-it-for","content":"<Card title=\"CLI & Script Developers\" description=\"Parse READMEs, changelogs, plan files, and API docs into structured data for automation, validation, and CI.\" />"},"290":{"id":"/docs-22","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#who-is-it-for","content":"<Card title=\"Application Developers\" description=\"Embed typed Markdown parsing into your app for user-generated content, configuration files, and documentation formats.\" />"},"291":{"id":"/docs-23","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Goal"},"292":{"id":"/docs-24","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Section"},"293":{"id":"/docs-25","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"New here?"},"294":{"id":"/docs-26","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Quickstart"},"295":{"id":"/docs-27","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Understand the architecture"},"296":{"id":"/docs-28","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Format SDK"},"297":{"id":"/docs-29","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Look up a function"},"298":{"id":"/docs-30","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"AST SDK"},"299":{"id":"/docs-31","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"See real formats"},"300":{"id":"/docs-32","page_id":"/docs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs#quick-navigation","content":"Examples"},"301":{"id":"/docs-33","page_id":"/docs","tags